    "location": "Family home visit, Lunar New Year",
    "context": "Lunar New Year (農曆新年) is the biggest celebration in the Chinese calendar. In Hong Kong, people visit relatives, exchange greetings (拜年), and give red packets of money (利是 lai si). Saying the right greetings matters — elders appreciate the effort.",
    "cultural_note": "The flower markets (花市, faa1 si5) that open across Hong Kong in the week before Lunar New Year are one of the city's great collective spectacles, hundreds of thousands of people cramming narrow stalls to buy kumquat trees, narcissus bulbs, and peach blossoms. The rush to buy the last flowers at midnight before New Year's Day, when vendors slash prices on remaining stock, is a competitive sport.",
